# Workflow Gatekeeper Process

Course review follows a **gated workflow**. Upon rejection, return feedback **limited to the stage that failed**. No cross-contamination: do not include grammar edits, style fixes, or other-stage feedback when rejecting for a specific stage.

## Stage 1 — Structural & Learning Architecture (Critical)

**Output:** Approve structure, or reject with **structural feedback only**. No grammar edits or micro rewrites.

| Checkpoint | How to check |
|------------|--------------|
| **Learn → Recognize → Recall** | Lesson has: concept intro → demonstration/example → practice/quiz/application. |
| **Clear learning objectives** | Course, module, and lesson start with measurable outcomes (action verbs: "create," "explain," not "understand"). |
| **Logical progression** | Prerequisites before advanced topics; map concept dependencies. |
| **Concepts before use** | Terms, syntax, and ideas defined or explained before use in code/examples. |
| **Cognitive load** | One new idea at a time; avoid dense theory + complex code + multiple new concepts at once. |
| **Not too many iterations** | Code example changed at most 3–4 times per lesson; no unnecessary recaps or loops. |
| **Appropriate scaffolding** | High support early, then gradual fading in later examples/challenges. |
| **Clear outcome** | Course/module states the concrete, demonstrable skill the learner will have. |
| **Flow toward outcome** | All content, examples, and exercises support the stated objective. |
| **Nothing out of order** | No practical example before theory; no summary in the middle of the lesson. |
| **Concepts, not just commands** | Explain *why* (concept/theory) as well as *how* (syntax/steps). |

## Stage 2 — Pedagogical Integrity (High)

| Checkpoint | How to check |
|------------|--------------|
| **Concepts before implementation** | Sequence: define concept → rationale → example code. No code-first-then-explanation. |
| **Abstract → concrete** | Abstract ideas linked to analogies, diagrams, or tangible examples. |
| **Misconceptions addressed** | Common errors or counter-intuitive behavior called out and corrected. |
| **Semantic waves (unplug → unpack → repack)** | General idea → concrete examples → consolidated abstract takeaway. |
| **Scaffolded examples** | First example simplest; add one new complexity at a time. |
| **PRIMM where appropriate** | Predict → Run → Investigate → Modify → Make for programming content. |
| **Learner agency** | Opportunities to decide, solve, and apply knowledge beyond copying steps. |
| **Understanding vs procedure** | Focus on transferable principles and logic, not only steps/syntax. |
| **Predict, modify, or create** | Exercises that require prediction, changing an example, or building something new. |
| **Balanced explanation** | Not over-explaining (burying the point) or under-supporting (missing context). |

## Stage 3 — Concept Clarity & Logical Integrity (Medium–High)

| Checkpoint | How to check |
|------------|--------------|
| **No unexplained terms** | Every technical term, acronym, or jargon defined on first use or linked to prior explanation. |
| **No acronym misuse** | Acronyms spelled out on first use; consistent form (e.g. "API" not "A.P.I."). |
| **No assumed prior knowledge** | Respect stated prerequisites; explain or avoid un-taught concepts. |
| **No circular explanations** | No A defined by B and B defined by A; use simpler, prior concepts. |
| **Examples match explanation** | Code/diagram/analogy matches the concept in the text. |
| **Code setup complete** | All setup (install, imports, config) provided or clearly instructed. |
| **Clear transitions** | Section/topic changes are signaled and logically justified. |

## Stage 4 — Instructional Precision & Technical Accuracy (Medium)

**Tool:** Run and verify.

| Checkpoint | How to check |
|------------|--------------|
| **Code runs** | All snippets and setup run without syntax/runtime errors. |
| **Outputs correct** | Shown results match actual output of provided code/instructions. |
| **No deprecated syntax** | Current, supported syntax for the stated language/framework version. |
| **Replicable** | Learner following instructions can get the same result from a clean start. |
| **No missing configuration** | All required files, env vars, dependencies, or config mentioned or created in steps. |

## Stage 5 — Editorial & Style Compliance (Low–Medium)

| Checkpoint | How to check |
|------------|--------------|
| **Second person "you"** | Address learner as "you"/"your"; avoid "we"/"us"/"our" for learner actions. |
| **Active voice** | Prefer strong active verbs; avoid passive where possible. |
| **Confident tone** | No hedging ("maybe," "perhaps," "might be confusing"). |
| **No selling/promotional language** | Instruction only; no marketing or hype. |
| **No redundant openers** | Cut filler starts ("Now, what we are going to do is..."). |
| **Consistent terminology** | Same names for concepts/variables throughout. |
| **Style guide alignment** | Matches org capitalization, tone, and style rules. |

## Stage 6 — Language Polish (Low)

| Checkpoint | How to check |
|------------|--------------|
| **Grammar and spelling** | No errors; use checker and human read-through. |
| **Punctuation** | Correct commas, semicolons, dashes, quotation marks. |
| **Sentence length** | Mix of short and longer sentences; avoid very long or repetitive runs. |
| **Readability** | Vocabulary and structure match target audience. |
| **Phrasing** | Refine clumsy or awkward sentences. |

## Stage 7 — Final Sanity & Read-Aloud Pass (Very Low)

**Manual.** No automated agent.

| Checkpoint | How to check |
|------------|--------------|
| **Reads aloud well** | Natural flow; no tongue-twisters or awkward pauses. |
| **No awkward phrasing** | Fix anything that stumbles in read-aloud. |
| **Minimal repetition** | Remove unnecessary restatement of the same point. |
| **Warm tone** | Encouraging and approachable, not cold. |
| **Micro clarity** | Every statement clear and unambiguous. |

## Applying This Rule

- When **reviewing for a specific stage**, use only that stage’s checkpoints. Do not mix in feedback from other stages.
- When **rejecting**, state the stage and list only the checkpoints that failed, with concrete references (e.g. section or line). Do not suggest grammar or style fixes when rejecting for Stage 1; do not suggest structural changes when rejecting for Stage 5 or 6.
